2 But a conditional declaration is [often] followed by a pure declaration, though this is not necessary, but is done ex superabim- danti. And the formulae are given, accusing the enemy of injustice. But that in this case, as we have said, such declaration is not neces- sary, appears from this, that it might be made to the nearest town occupied by troops, as the Feciales announced, when they were con- sulted about the case of Philip of Macedon, and afterwards of Antio- chus, since the first declaration of war was to be made by him who was attacked. In the war with Pyrrhus, the declaration was made to one of the soldiers of Pyrrhus, and this was done in the circus of Flaminius, when the soldier was compelled formally to purchase his place in order to be a party to the cause, as Servius relates on the ninth book of the AEneid.
